<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="339" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1618,2003]" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1618,1643]" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Viets" authorityYear="1913" box="[452,606,1618,1643]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Axonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="8" pageNumber="339" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[452,606,1618,1643]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">Axonopsalbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like mites as given by 
<bibRefCitation box="[890,1042,1618,1643]" pageId="8" pageNumber="339" refId="ref7104" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mite genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 860." type="journal article">Cook (1974)</bibRefCitation>
: Dorsal and ventral shields fused posteriorly; lateroglandularia fused with dorsal shield; two pairs of glandular platelets located near the anterior margin of ventral shield, no glandularia in the dorsal furrow; tips of Cx-I not extending to frontal idiosoma margin; Cx-IV with two pairs of glandularia, one located immediately medial, the other posterior to IV-L-insertions; projections associated with openings of IV-L-insertions relatively long and bluntly pointed; three pairs of genital acetabula. Male: Posterior end of dorsal shield modified as illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[983,1074,1798,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1948,1970]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,195,1937]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,185,1937]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Lagoenaxonopsalbia comorosensis sp. nov., male holotype, Hajangoua stream, Mayotte: A = dorsal; B = ventral; C = cauda, ventral view; D = gnathosoma and palp; E = palp; F = I-L; G = IV-L; H = ejaculatory complex. Scale bars = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437796/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
, forming a well developed axeshaped cauda; excretory pore on a separate plate lying on the caudal portion of the dorsal shield, excretory pore plate more elevated in the centre, almost circular in lateral view, with paired groups of long setae flanking the excretory pore and paired glandularia associated with humps. Female: Excretory pore lying at extreme end of dorsal shield (
<figureCitation box="[316,409,1942,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,272,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,265,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Lagoenaxonopsalbia comorosensis sp. nov., female (A–C, F from River Antanana, D–E from River Djalimou, Mayotte): A = dorsal shield; B = ventral; C = genital field; D = gnathosoma and palp; D = palp (P-1 lacking); E = palp; F = gential plate region. Scale bars = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437798/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
); acetabula-bearing plates and postgenital sclerite fused with the dorsal shield; a pair of glandularia near the anterior margins of the acetabula-bearing genital plates fused to the ventral shield (
<figureCitation box="[1309,1397,1978,2003]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1932,1954]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,272,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,265,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Lagoenaxonopsalbia comorosensis sp. nov., female (A–C, F from River Antanana, D–E from River Djalimou, Mayotte): A = dorsal shield; B = ventral; C = genital field; D = gnathosoma and palp; D = palp (P-1 lacking); E = palp; F = gential plate region. Scale bars = 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437798/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="339">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,851,151,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,851,151,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,151,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Type species</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Pešić &amp; Smit &amp; Mary, 2018" authorityName="Pešić &amp; Smit &amp; Mary" authorityYear="2018" box="[362,755,151,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Lagoenaxonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comorosensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[362,755,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Lagoenaxonopsalbia comorosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[762,851,151,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[762,851,151,176]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="340" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,188,213]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Remarks</emphasis>
. The combination of a well developed flask-shaped idiosoma with a large, widened cauda, the genital field with the gonopore located in terminal position on the cauda, flanked by three pairs of acetabula, and the excretory pore plate elevated in the centre and almost circular in lateral view, lying on the caudal portion of the dorsal shield, will easily distinguish the male of the new genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">
The combination of relatively long projections associated with the openings of IV-L-insertions, the acetabulabearing plates fused with the postgenital sclerite and the presence of a pair of glandularia medially to the insertions of IV-L, makes the female of the new species most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="K. Viets, 1913" authorityName="K. Viets" authorityYear="1913" box="[839,1162,404,429]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Axonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[839,993,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Axonopsalbia</emphasis>
K. Viets, 1913
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Cook, 1974" authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1974" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Pseudaxonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Motasaxona">
<emphasis box="[1217,1436,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Pseudaxonopsalbia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[160,299,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Motasaxona</emphasis>
) 
<bibRefCitation box="[318,455,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" refId="ref7104" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mite genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 860." type="journal article">Cook, 1974</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The females of the latter two taxa can be distinguished from the new species in: 1) dorsal furrow with three pairs of small glandularia platelets, all restricted to the posterior half, and not fused to dorsal shield, 2) two pairs of glandularia typically fused to anterior margin of ventral shield, 3) genital field with 4 pairs of acetabula, and 4) the glandularia located near the anterior margins of the acetabula-bearing genital plates free, not fused with the ventral shield. The latter character state is also found in females of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cook, 1999" authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1999" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Villaxonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Villaxonopsalbia sudafricana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[292,425,620,645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" refId="ref7132" refString="Cook, D. R. (1999) Axonopsalbia - like water mites from South Africa (Acari, Hydrachnida, Aturidae). International Journal of Acarology, 25 (4), 317 - 327. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01647959908684170" type="journal article">Cook, 1999</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, representative of a monotypic genus known from South Africa. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1999" box="[1152,1341,620,645]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Villaxonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1152,1341,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Villaxonopsalbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females are unique among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Viets" authorityYear="1913" box="[360,514,655,680]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Axonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[360,514,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Axonopsalbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like mites in the fusion of the excretory pore with the combined acetabular plates and postgenital sclerite (
<bibRefCitation box="[424,553,692,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" refId="ref7132" refString="Cook, D. R. (1999) Axonopsalbia - like water mites from South Africa (Acari, Hydrachnida, Aturidae). International Journal of Acarology, 25 (4), 317 - 327. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01647959908684170" type="journal article">Cook 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1367,727,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,1367,727,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,727,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Etymology</emphasis>
. The new genus name is a combination of 
<emphasis box="[806,1151,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">lagoena (Latin, = bottle, flask)</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Viets" authorityYear="1913" box="[1206,1360,727,752]" class="Arachnida" family="Aturidae" genus="Axonopsalbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1206,1360,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="340">Axonopsalbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
